{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Go to git-scm.com in your web browser. Click the large Download button on the homepage. The download will start automatically for your operating system.",
      "title": "Download Git"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the downloaded installer file in your Downloads folder. On Windows, it's named like 'Git-2.43.0-64-bit.exe'. On Mac, it's a .dmg or .pkg file. Double-click to open it.",
      "title": "Open the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Windows, click 'Next' through the setup screens using the default options. On Mac, drag Git to Applications or follow the installer prompts. Click 'Install' when ready.",
      "title": "Run the Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "Wait for the progress bar to complete. This usually takes 1-2 minutes. When finished, you'll see a completion message. Click 'Finish' or 'Close' to exit the installer.",
      "title": "Complete Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your terminal (Mac/Linux) or Command Prompt (Windows). Type 'git --version' and press Enter. You should see output like 'git version 2.43.0' confirming Git is installed.",
      "title": "Verify Git is Installed"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Place wheel chocks behind the tires opposite to the flat tire. If the flat is on the front, chock the rear tires. This prevents the car from rolling.",
      "title": "Secure the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use the lug wrench to loosen each lug nut by turning counterclockwise. Only turn them about half a turn — don't remove them yet. The tire should still be on the ground.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the jacking point near the flat tire — look for a reinforced metal area under the car's frame. Consult your owner's manual if unsure. Place the jack directly under this point.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the jack handle clockwise to raise the car. Lift until the flat tire is about 6 inches off the ground. The tire should spin freely without touching the pavement.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove each lug nut completely by turning counterclockwise with your fingers or the wrench. Place them in a safe spot like your pocket or inside the hubcap so they don't roll away.",
      "title": "Remove the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grip the tire firmly with both hands at 3 and 9 o'clock positions. Pull it straight toward you to remove it from the wheel hub. Set it flat on the ground away from traffic.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Flat Tire"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Boil fresh, filtered water in a kettle. You'll need about 17 ounces (500ml) for a standard 3-cup French press. Remove from heat when it reaches a rolling boil.",
      "title": "Boil the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Let the boiled water sit for 30 seconds. This brings the temperature to about 200°F (93°C), which is ideal for coffee extraction.",
      "title": "Cool Water Slightly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Add 3 tablespoons (about 20g) of coarsely ground coffee to the empty French press. The grounds should look like breadcrumbs, not powder.",
      "title": "Add Coffee Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour just enough hot water to cover the grounds, about 2 ounces (60ml). This allows the coffee to \"bloom\" and release trapped gases.",
      "title": "Start the Bloom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Wait 30 seconds while the coffee blooms. You'll see the grounds bubble and rise slightly. This step enhances flavor extraction.",
      "title": "Let Coffee Bloom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the remaining hot water in a slow, circular motion until the French press is filled to about 1 inch below the metal band. Avoid pouring directly onto the grounds in one spot.",
      "title": "Add Remaining Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the lid on the French press with the plunger pulled all the way up. Don't press down yet. The lid keeps heat in during brewing.",
      "title": "Cover with Lid"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set a timer for 4 minutes. This is the ideal brew time for French press coffee. Avoid the temptation to stir or disturb the coffee.",
      "title": "Set Timer for 4 Minutes"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the timer goes off, slowly press the plunger down using steady, even pressure. The plunge should take about 20-30 seconds. Stop if you feel strong resistance.",
      "title": "Press the Plunger Down"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coffee immediately into your cup or a separate carafe. Leaving coffee in the French press continues extraction and makes it bitter.",
      "title": "Pour Coffee Immediately"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enjoy your coffee within 5-10 minutes for the best flavor. The coffee should taste rich, full-bodied, and smooth without bitterness.",
      "title": "Serve and Enjoy"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Choose a sunny spot in your garden that receives at least 6-8 hours of direct sunlight daily. Mark out an area about 3 feet by 3 feet for each tomato plant you plan to grow.",
      "title": "Select Your Planting Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove all weeds, rocks, and debris from the marked area. Pull weeds by their roots to prevent regrowth. Clear the surface completely before moving to the next step.",
      "title": "Clear the Surface"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a garden fork or spade to loosen the soil to a depth of 12-15 inches. Push the tool in vertically, then rock it back and forth to break up compacted soil. Work your way across the entire planting area.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Break up any large soil clumps by hitting them with the back of your spade or crushing them with your hands. The soil should be crumbly, not in hard chunks.",
      "title": "Break Up Clumps"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 2-3 inch layer of compost or well-rotted manure evenly across the loosened soil. This adds nutrients and improves soil structure for healthy root growth.",
      "title": "Add Organic Matter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sprinkle a balanced fertilizer (like 10-10-10) across the bed following package directions for tomatoes. Typically this is about 2-3 pounds per 100 square feet.",
      "title": "Apply Fertilizer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your garden fork to mix the compost and fertilizer into the top 8-10 inches of soil. Turn and blend thoroughly until amendments are evenly distributed throughout.",
      "title": "Mix in Amendments"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rake the surface smooth and level. Remove any remaining stones or debris. The bed should have a slight crown in the center to help with drainage.",
      "title": "Level the Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Water the prepared bed thoroughly until the soil is moist 6-8 inches deep. Check by pushing your finger into the soil—it should feel damp but not waterlogged.",
      "title": "Water the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Let the bed rest for 2-3 days before planting. This allows the amendments to settle and begin integrating with the soil. The bed is ready when the surface is slightly dry but soil beneath remains moist.",
      "title": "Allow Soil to Settle"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Lay your fabric flat on a large, clean surface with the wrong side facing up. Smooth out any wrinkles or folds with your hands.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Work Surface"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place your measuring tape along the fabric's edge. Measure 27 inches across and mark with a fabric pencil or chalk. This is your pillowcase width.",
      "title": "Mark the Width"
    },
    {
      "text": "From the same starting edge, measure 41 inches down the fabric's length. Mark this point with your fabric pencil. This is your pillowcase length.",
      "title": "Mark the Length"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using your ruler as a straight edge, draw a line connecting your width marks across the top. Draw another line connecting your length marks down the side.",
      "title": "Draw Cutting Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place pins every 3-4 inches along the lines you drew. The pins should go through both fabric layers if your fabric is folded, or just one layer if flat.",
      "title": "Pin the Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using fabric scissors, carefully cut along the marked lines. Keep the scissors perpendicular to the fabric and use long, smooth strokes for clean edges.",
      "title": "Cut the Main Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure and mark a second piece 27 inches wide by 10 inches long. This is your cuff piece. Pin and cut it the same way as the main piece.",
      "title": "Cut the Cuff Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold both pieces up and check that edges are straight and measurements match. The main piece should be 27x41 inches, the cuff 27x10 inches.",
      "title": "Verify Your Pieces"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Download a free guitar tuner app on your phone (like GuitarTuna or Fender Tune) or get a clip-on tuner. Open the app or turn on your tuner.",
      "title": "Get a Tuner Ready"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold your guitar in playing position. The thickest string (closest to your face) is the 6th string. This is the Low E string we'll tune first.",
      "title": "Identify the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 6th string (Low E) with your picking hand. Let it ring clearly without touching other strings.",
      "title": "Play the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Watch your tuner display. If the needle or indicator shows flat (too low), turn the tuning peg away from you. If sharp (too high), turn it toward you. Adjust until the tuner shows perfectly in tune.",
      "title": "Adjust Until E Shows Green"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 5th string (A string - second thickest). Watch the tuner and turn its tuning peg until the display shows A and lights up green or centered.",
      "title": "Tune the A String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string (D string - middle thickness). Adjust its tuning peg until your tuner confirms it's perfectly tuned to D.",
      "title": "Tune the D String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 3rd string (G string). Turn its peg until the tuner shows G and indicates it's in tune.",
      "title": "Tune the G String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string (B string - second thinnest). Adjust until your tuner confirms it's tuned to B.",
      "title": "Tune the B String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 1st string (High E - thinnest string farthest from your face). Tune it until the display shows E and confirms it's in tune.",
      "title": "Tune the High E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Go back and pluck each string from 6th to 1st again. The tuner should show green for all. If any drifted, make small adjustments. Your guitar is tuned when all six strings check out.",
      "title": "Verify All Strings"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Turn your camera's mode dial to 'M' for Manual mode. The dial is usually on top of the camera body. You should see 'M' displayed in the viewfinder or on the LCD screen.",
      "title": "Switch to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Point your camera at your subject and half-press the shutter button. Look at the exposure meter in your viewfinder - it's a scale with numbers from -2 to +2. Note where the indicator sits.",
      "title": "Check the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the ISO button (often labeled 'ISO') and rotate the main dial to adjust the ISO value. Start with ISO 400 for indoor lighting or ISO 100 for bright outdoor scenes.",
      "title": "Set Your ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look through the viewfinder and rotate the aperture dial (or hold the aperture button and rotate the main dial). Lower f-numbers (like f/2.8) let in more light; higher f-numbers (like f/16) let in less.",
      "title": "Adjust the Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the shutter speed dial (or the main dial if aperture is set separately). Faster speeds like 1/500 darken the image; slower speeds like 1/60 brighten it. Watch the exposure meter move as you adjust.",
      "title": "Set the Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Half-press the shutter button again and check the exposure meter. The indicator should be near the center (0) for proper exposure. If it's to the left, increase light. If it's to the right, decrease light.",
      "title": "Verify Proper Exposure"
    },
    {
      "text": "Make small adjustments to shutter speed or aperture until the meter indicator sits at or near 0. Avoid changing ISO unless necessary, as higher ISO adds grain to your image.",
      "title": "Fine-Tune Your Settings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fully press the shutter button to take a test photo. Review it on your LCD screen. Check the histogram - peaks should be centered, not bunched at the edges.",
      "title": "Take a Test Shot"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the image is too dark, decrease your shutter speed or open your aperture (lower f-number). If too bright, increase shutter speed or close your aperture (higher f-number). Retake until satisfied.",
      "title": "Adjust and Reshoot"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, toes pointing slightly outward at about 15 degrees. Keep your arms relaxed at your sides. You should feel balanced and stable.",
      "title": "Position Your Feet"
    },
    {
      "text": "Engage your core by pulling your belly button toward your spine. Keep your chest up and your shoulders back. Look straight ahead or slightly upward to maintain neutral neck alignment.",
      "title": "Set Your Upper Body"
    },
    {
      "text": "Shift your weight to your heels and begin bending your knees while pushing your hips back, as if sitting into a chair. Keep your chest lifted throughout the movement.",
      "title": "Initiate the Descent"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue lowering until your thighs are parallel to the floor or slightly below. Your knees should track over your toes, not caving inward. You should feel tension in your thighs and glutes.",
      "title": "Lower to Depth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check that your knees haven't moved past your toes and your back maintains its natural curve. Your weight should be in your heels, and you should be able to wiggle your toes slightly.",
      "title": "Verify Bottom Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press through your heels and drive your hips forward to return to standing. Keep your core engaged and chest up. Exhale as you rise.",
      "title": "Push Back Up"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stand fully upright with hips fully extended. Your body should form a straight line from head to heels. This is your starting position for the next repetition.",
      "title": "Complete the Movement"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Aqueça 1 xícara de água até ficar morna (cerca de 37°C). Teste com o dedo — deve estar confortável, nem quente nem fria. Água muito quente mata o fermento.",
      "title": "Aqueça a água"
    },
    {
      "text": "Adicione 1 colher de sopa de açúcar e 1 colher de sopa de fermento biológico seco na água morna. Mexa levemente e deixe descansar por 10 minutos.",
      "title": "Ative o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Observe a mistura após 10 minutos. Ela deve estar espumosa e com bolhas na superfície. Se não espumar, o fermento está vencido — comece novamente com fermento novo.",
      "title": "Verifique a ativação"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela grande, adicione 3 xícaras de farinha de trigo, 1 colher de chá de sal e 2 colheres de sopa de óleo. Misture os ingredientes secos com uma colher.",
      "title": "Misture os ingredientes secos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje a mistura de fermento ativado sobre os ingredientes secos. Mexa com uma colher de pau até formar uma massa grudenta e desigual.",
      "title": "Adicione o fermento ativado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Polvilhe farinha na bancada limpa. Transfira a massa para a bancada e comece a sovar, dobrando e pressionando com as palmas das mãos.",
      "title": "Comece a sovar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sove a massa por 10 minutos, adicionando pequenas quantidades de farinha se grudar muito. A massa deve ficar lisa, elástica e não grudar nas mãos.",
      "title": "Sove até ficar elástica"
    },
    {
      "text": "Faça o teste da janela: estique um pedaço pequeno da massa. Se formar uma película fina e translúcida sem rasgar, a massa está pronta. Se rasgar facilmente, sove mais 2-3 minutos.",
      "title": "Teste a elasticidade"
    },
    {
      "text": "Unte uma tigela limpa com óleo. Coloque a massa dentro, virando-a para untar toda a superfície. Isso evita que resseque durante o descanso.",
      "title": "Unte a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cubra a tigela com um pano limpo ou filme plástico. Deixe descansar em local morno por 1 hora. A massa deve dobrar de tamanho — esse é o sinal de que está pronta para modelar.",
      "title": "Deixe a massa crescer"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Localiza la llave de paso debajo del lavabo o fregadero. Gírala completamente en sentido horario hasta que no pueda moverse más. Abre el grifo para confirmar que no sale agua.",
      "title": "Cierra el suministro de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca un tapón en el desagüe o cubre el área con un trapo. Esto evitará que las piezas pequeñas caigan por el drenaje mientras trabajas.",
      "title": "Protege el desagüe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Busca el tornillo decorativo en la manija del grifo. Usa un destornillador para quitarlo y levanta la manija hacia arriba. Si está atascada, muévela suavemente de lado a lado mientras tiras.",
      "title": "Retira la manija del grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Verás una tuerca hexagonal alrededor del cartucho. Usa una llave ajustable para aflojarla girando en sentido antihorario. Retira la tuerca completamente con la mano.",
      "title": "Afloja la tuerca de sujeción"
    },
    {
      "text": "Toma el cartucho firmemente y tira hacia arriba para sacarlo. Si está pegado, muévelo ligeramente de lado a lado. Observa cómo está orientado para instalarlo correctamente después.",
      "title": "Extrae el cartucho o empaque"
    },
    {
      "text": "Revisa el empaque de goma dentro del cartucho. Si está agrietado, desgastado o rígido, necesita reemplazo. Lleva el cartucho completo a la ferretería para conseguir el repuesto exacto.",
      "title": "Inspecciona las piezas dañadas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Limpia el interior del cuerpo del grifo con un trapo húmedo. Retira cualquier residuo de minerales o suciedad que pueda causar fugas. Asegúrate de que la superficie esté completamente seca.",
      "title": "Limpia el área de montaje"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca el cartucho nuevo en la misma posición que el anterior. Empújalo firmemente hacia abajo hasta que encaje completamente. La orientación debe coincidir con las ranuras internas.",
      "title": "Instala el cartucho nuevo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Vuelve a colocar la tuerca hexagonal y apriétala con la llave ajustable. Gírala en sentido horario hasta que esté firme, pero sin excederte para no dañar las roscas.",
      "title": "Ajusta la tuerca de sujeción"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca la manija de vuelta en su posición, alineando el orificio con el tornillo. Inserta y aprieta el tornillo decorativo con el destornillador hasta que la manija quede firme.",
      "title": "Reinstala la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gira la llave de paso debajo del lavabo en sentido antihorario para abrir el agua completamente. Abre el grifo lentamente para liberar el aire atrapado en las tuberías.",
      "title": "Abre el suministro de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cierra el grifo y observa durante varios minutos. No debe gotear. Si ves goteo, es posible que necesites apretar más la tuerca o verificar que el cartucho esté bien instalado.",
      "title": "Verifica que no haya fugas"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Click the \"File\" menu in the top-left corner of your word processor. The menu will expand to show various file operations.",
      "title": "Open File Menu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Select \"Save\" from the dropdown menu, or press Ctrl+S (Windows) or Cmd+S (Mac) as a shortcut. The Save dialog will appear if this is your first time saving.",
      "title": "Choose Save Option"
    },
    {
      "text": "Navigate to the folder where you want to store the document. Click folders to open them until you reach your desired location, such as Documents or a project folder.",
      "title": "Select Save Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type a descriptive name for your document in the \"File name\" field. Choose something you'll recognize later, like \"Meeting Notes - January 2024\".",
      "title": "Name Your Document"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the \"Save\" button at the bottom of the dialog. The dialog will close and you'll see your document name appear in the title bar, confirming it's saved.",
      "title": "Confirm and Save"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Place the motherboard box on your work surface and open it. Remove the motherboard and set it on top of the anti-static bag it came in. This provides a safe, non-conductive surface for installation.",
      "title": "Prepare the Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the metal CPU retention arm on the motherboard socket. Push it down and to the side to release it. The socket cover will pop up slightly when unlocked.",
      "title": "Open the CPU Socket"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the CPU from its plastic case by lifting straight up—never touch the gold contacts on the bottom. Align the gold triangle on the CPU corner with the triangle on the socket.",
      "title": "Position the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lower the CPU straight down into the socket without forcing it. It should drop in smoothly with all pins aligned. If it doesn't seat easily, lift it out and check the alignment again.",
      "title": "Install the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lower the retention arm back down and push it under the locking clip until it clicks. You'll need to apply firm pressure—this is normal and secures the CPU properly.",
      "title": "Lock the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Peel the protective film off the CPU cooler base if present. Apply a pea-sized dot of thermal paste to the center of the CPU if your cooler didn't come with paste pre-applied.",
      "title": "Apply Thermal Paste"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the CPU cooler on top of the CPU, aligning the mounting brackets with the holes around the socket. Press down gently but firmly to spread the thermal paste evenly.",
      "title": "Mount the CPU Cooler"
    },
    {
      "text": "Secure the cooler using the mounting mechanism (screws or clips). Tighten in an X-pattern if using screws, alternating between opposite corners. The cooler should be firmly attached with no wobble.",
      "title": "Secure the Cooler"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the CPU fan header on the motherboard, labeled \"CPU_FAN\" near the socket. Plug in the cooler's power cable—it only fits one way with the clip facing a specific direction.",
      "title": "Connect Cooler Power"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open the RAM slots by pushing the clips at each end outward until they click. Check your motherboard manual to see which slots to use first (usually slots 2 and 4 for two sticks).",
      "title": "Prepare RAM Slots"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold the RAM stick by the edges and align the notch in the middle with the ridge in the slot. The notch is off-center, so the RAM only fits one way.",
      "title": "Align the RAM"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press down firmly on both ends of the RAM stick until the clips automatically snap up and lock into place. You'll hear two distinct clicks when properly seated.",
      "title": "Install RAM Modules"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the I/O shield that came with your case (metal rectangle in the rear). Press the motherboard's custom I/O shield into the case opening from inside until all edges click into place.",
      "title": "Install I/O Shield"
    },
    {
      "text": "Screw in the motherboard standoffs into the case at positions matching your motherboard's mounting holes. Most cases have these pre-installed, but verify they align with your board size.",
      "title": "Install Standoffs"
    },
    {
      "text": "Carefully lower the motherboard into the case, aligning the rear ports with the I/O shield cutouts. Rest it on the standoffs and check that all mounting holes line up.",
      "title": "Position Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Insert motherboard screws through the mounting holes and tighten them in a star pattern—alternate between opposite corners. Don't overtighten; snug is enough to secure without damaging the board.",
      "title": "Secure Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the 24-pin ATX power connector on the motherboard's right edge. Align the clip on the cable with the tab on the connector and push firmly until you hear a click.",
      "title": "Connect Main Power"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the 4-pin or 8-pin CPU power connector near the top-left of the motherboard. Plug in the corresponding cable from your PSU, pressing until the clip locks.",
      "title": "Connect CPU Power"
    },
    {
      "text": "Identify the case front panel connectors—small cables labeled PWR_SW, RESET, HDD LED, and PWR LED. Consult your motherboard manual for the exact pin layout on the front panel header.",
      "title": "Locate Front Panel Cables"
    },
    {
      "text": "Plug in the power switch connector (PWR_SW) to the designated pins. This is the only essential connection—the PC won't turn on without it. Polarity doesn't matter for power switches.",
      "title": "Connect Power Switch"
    },
    {
      "text": "Connect the remaining front panel cables according to your manual. LED cables are polarized—match the positive wire (usually colored or marked) to the positive pin.",
      "title": "Connect LED Cables"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the USB 3.0 header on the motherboard (blue, about 1 inch long). Align the USB 3.0 cable from the case—it only fits one way due to a missing pin—and press firmly to connect.",
      "title": "Connect Front USB"
    },
    {
      "text": "If your case has an audio jack, locate the HD AUDIO header on the motherboard (usually bottom-left). Plug in the front panel audio connector, aligning the missing pin with the blocked socket hole.",
      "title": "Connect Front Audio"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the appropriate PCIe slot covers from the case rear where your GPU will be installed (usually the top 2 or 3 slots). Unscrew or pop them out depending on your case design.",
      "title": "Remove PCIe Covers"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open the PCIe x16 slot clip (usually the top slot) by pushing it to the side. Hold your GPU by the bracket and edges, carefully aligning the gold contacts with the PCIe slot.",
      "title": "Prepare GPU Slot"
    },
    {
